title: For Sale:  NOW $700!!! COLT 1883 Hammerless Side By Side 12 Ga Shotgun Damascus Barrels & Engraving
postcontent:
I have for trade a very early all original Colt 1883 Hammerless 12 Guage shotgun. There are three grades of these guns per the year it was made. This is the in the middle of 3 grades model. The Deluxe. All Colt shotguns were custom order one at a time in 1883. I'm too cheap to buy the letter from colt or it would be worth a lot more. VERY low all matching serial numbers throughout every piece of the gun. Tight action. Locks perfectly like a Swiss watch. Real Damascus laid barrels in excellent shape all the way down. There is about 40-60 percent of the finish intact. I'm no expert which is why I left the margin that wide. That's not rust or patina u see on the metal. In 1883 steel wasn't blued. It was either browned or case acid blued. This like all finer guns was browned. So what remains is about half of its browning. Barrels never touched. No major dings. Inside bores are excellent for the age. Heavy engraving in very good shape. The forend is in good shape which is rare for these 131 year old guns. The buttstock has the silver inlay proof coin intact and excellent. Both triggers work very well. 
Now for the bad. The stock is cracked obviously at the pistol grip. It was repaired early in the 1900s according to the former owner. And it shows that age. It's gapped poorly and will either need a new stock which is very hard to track down if original. And the Bakelite? I'm guessing buttplate which is correct Colt, is cracked. A screw in the trigger guard bottom metal was replaced with an obvious wrong screw it looks like decades ago. All the other screws, bolts and hardware on the gun are original and in great shape. I have found a source for buttplate and that screw, correct from colt for under $30 for both. As far as the stock goes...my first instinct was to replace it. And while I did find several colt 1883 stocks, I realized that making the finish shiny in spots and messing with 131 year old patina on most of the gun to do that swap would devalue it quite a bit.  These are rare as hens teeth and on the net from anywhere from $1400 in rougher shape than mine to-$12,000 for perfect.  
$700 cash

title: For Sale/Trade:  FS/FT 1809 Harpers Ferry
postcontent: 1809 Harpers Ferry flintlock .50 rifle.  Was built by renowned gun builder Steve Krolick.  Has 42" match grade swamped barrel.  A Ketland lock with 3 1/2 lb trigger pull.  Yes, it is a Schimmel rifle. Also known as a "Southern boy rifle". It was a copy of one found during the civil war. The Southerners usually repurposed old gun parts. It is not a full copy however, it is made to shoot and be accurate. It is a Green Mountain Barrel from A.I.S.I. 1137 modified, stress relieved, annealed, certified rifle barrel steel. 7/8 barrel size, 14-1/4 trigger reach and 7.2 pounds. It has 8 lands and grooves with a 1 in 70" twist. It was inspiried by the book "The Southern Arsenal" by Dr. James Whisker on page 40. The vent hole has also been internally coned. The rear sight is 11-1/2" inches forward of the breech for us old shooters. It has buckhorn rear sight. It is an L&R flintlock. The trigger bow is of the 1803 style with inspectors initials. title: For Sale:  Japanese Arisaka Type 99 Rifle
location: Lock Haven, North Central, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent: For Sale:  Arisaka Type 99 Rifle in 7.7x58 caliber.  This is a “Last Ditch” rifle with a completely intact mum, and was most likely manufactured at the Kokura Arsenal.   As a rifle of this type, the wood is roughly prepared but remains in good condition.  As expected, it has a rear peep sight and a wooden butt pad.  The metal is in good condition and the rifle is complete.  The bolt knob, firing pin and spring are from an original rifle, but are not the ones from this rifle.  Those parts, by popular opinion, are probably rusting away on the floor of the Pacific Ocean.  This suggests that the rifle is a captured, bring-back unit, but I can only speculate on this.  The bore of this rifle is not chrome lined, but it still shows strong rifling.  These rifles have some of the strongest actions ever manufactured.  It has been disassembled, gently cleaned and oiled, and re-assembled.  Price is $250.  Rifle can be shipped at buyer’s expense.

title: For Sale:  Collectors: 1959 Ruger Blackhawk .44 Magnum Single Action Revolver, Flat-Top, 3 Screw  Must See
postcontent: I just got off of the phone with Ruger, I called to have them check the serial number on my Ruger Pistol and give me the date that it was manufactured and after lots of digging in the archives and other old files he found out that my Ruger Blackhawk .44 Magnum Pistol was produced in 1959 which makes it 55 Years Old. The serial number is #15580 in case you want to verify this information. The Gun is as stated above, a 1959 Ruger Blackhawk .44 Magnum Single Action Revolver, it's the "Flat Top" Design with an Adjustable Sight that says "Micro" inside of the sight in cursive writing and also has the famous "3 SCREW" Design. This Gun has the legendary smooth action and perfect trigger these older Blackhawks are known for, this gun cycles so easily and honestly has the smoothest action of any gun I have ever felt, the trigger pulls effortlessly and all of that contributes to this being one of the most accurate guns you could ever own. has the 6.5" Barrel and has the factory equipped, optional "STAG" brand Grips, they are an Ivory Color with Black Accents- the upgrade from the factory Walnut Color Grips cost $16.50 back in 1959. This Gun doesn't have a lot of writing and warnings on it like a lot of the modern guns do, just the Serial Number "15580" written under the cylinder on the right side of the gun, on the left side in the same place it says: "RUGER BLACKHAWK 44 MAGNUM CALIBER" in small letters and the left side of the Barrel says: "STURM, RUGER & CO. SOUTHPORT, CONN U.S.A.". The Gun is totally original and hasn't ever been sent back to Ruger for anything. The finish is original also and still looks great and the bluing still shines like it did when it was new. The Gun looks great overall and only has a few minor scratches and some normal wear but still looks great and everything functions flawlessly.The Gun has been shot very little over the years, but is an extremely powerful and ACCURATE gun that should drop anything in its path easily. Thet factory rifling in the Barrel is 100% PERFECT and looks new. This Gun has been in the family since it was new but it's time for it to move on to a new home. This would be an excellent gun for any collection and even though its 55 years old, it'll still be like getting a New Gun because this gun looks awesome, and functions smoother and feels better than any new Revolver I've ever handled, you'll just have to see and feel it in person. Subject: No Mass.- style gun laws in VT; please come to Legislative Mixer 3/13/14


The Burlington, Vermont City Council is seeking to enact gun restrictions that would affect all of Vermont because it would require the Legislature to make an exception to the VT Sportsmen's Bill of Rights (24 V.S.A. Sec 2295).



Burlington's advocates of civilian disarmament have said that they want to see Vermont as a whole enact regulations of firearms similar to those found in neighboring states like Massachusetts.



Once Burlington gets an exception to Section 2295, which requires that only the State can enact restrictions on possession of firearms, other towns will surely follow, creating a crazy quilt of varying restrictions around the State.



Burlington has hired some of the most influential and politically correct lobbyists in Vermont, who have a constant presence in the Legislature throughout the entire Legislative Session, and a track record of success.



These promoters of gun restrictions in Vermont are trying to tell legislators that "things have changed in Vermont" and that outdoorspeople have died off or stopped caring about these issues.



The Vermont Federation of Sportsmen's Clubs is having a "Legislative Mixer" on Thursday March 13, in the State House cafeteria (enter by the front entrances to the building and keep following the halls to the very back of the building along the hillside), from 4:30- 8:00 PM.



This is NOT a protest or demonstration.



It is a chance to interact with Legislators and fellow outdoors people to show that Vermont voters and citizens care about these issues.



There is free food, and it is good food.


To get a sense of what to expect if Vermont follows the Massachusetts approach often touted by those who want to restrict guns in Vermont, have a look at this:




Burlington's efforts are being steered and advised by out-of-state gun-ban groups, and represent the biggest threat on these issues in Vermont.



Size matters: Legislators will be paying close attention to how many people show up. A small turnout will play into the hands of the lobbyists who say that no one cares. Your attendance matters. Please come, and please tell and bring friends who also care about these issues.

title: For Sale:  Collectors: 1944 Walther/Spreewerke CVG P38 Nickel Plated  9mm used in World War 2 Germany Must See This One!
postcontent:
Walther was the original manufacturer of the P38 Pistol but during World War 2 they were not able to produce enough of them to keep up with demand and they contracted Mauser and Spreewerke to make them. We have all heard of Mauser, for those of you who aren't familiar with Sprerwerke- they started out making large weapons like anti-aircraft guns, etc. but by the end of World War 2 they were producing 10,000 P38 9mm Pistols each month, this is one of them. A select few were produced with the Nickel Plated Finish. This was brought back from Europe when World War 2 was over with and was not shipped over here later by an Importer and this isn't a Russian-Capture like a lot of P38 Pistols ended up being. This Spreewerke made Pistol has a Walther Barrel and Action, the highly sought after "Bakelite" Grips, 2 Mauser 8 Round Magazines and the Black Bandolier this unit was issued and carried in. This Gun is beautiful inside and out and basically Flawless, it is still 100% Function and is simply beautiful. It was common for the P38 Pistols like this to have parts from the 3 major manufacturers of the Weapon. I do have an idea of how much money I need for this pistol but

Numbered and authenticated.
Discontinued in 1998

This is a German police surplus gun issued NEW in Germany.

The SIG P6 is a more compact version of the SIG P220. The Swiss Army wanted semi-automatic handgun, that would provide excellent functionality with a double-action trigger. The 9mm SIG-Sauer P6, debuted with various new and inventive features. It utilized a single column magazine holding eight 9 mm rounds and has a 3.9 in. barrel.

A new German police standard, in the mid-1970s, prompted SIG-Sauer to develop a new pistol that met the standard: The SIG-Sauer P225 (known as the P6) and the Heckler & Koch P7. The SIG-Sauer P225 was the least expensive (due mainly to the inventive design) and received the majority of the orders. To be able to manufacture that many handguns, SIG acquired a controlling interest in J. P. Sauer & Sohn in Eckenförde, Germany to manufacture parts. This is also where all P225s were manufactured. The only difference between the P6 and P225 — the P225 (which was adopted by US civilian law enforcement) has a lighter trigger pull, whereas the P6's trigger pull is heavier. The P225 has tritium fixed sights; P6's have fixed sights only. Because of its compact size, the P225/P6 is quite readily usable for concealed carry. In U.S. states where high-capacity magazines were prohibited, the P6/P225 is in high demand.
